Leaders yesterday joined Kenyans in mourning Nyeri Governor Nderitu Gachagua, 64 (pictured).He died at 2.15am yesterday morning at the Royal Marsden Hospital in London, following a long battle with pancreatic cancer. In a statement, President Uhuru Kenyatta sent his condolences to the family, friends and relatives of the governor.He said Gachagua was a great leader and an action-oriented man who served Nyeri with diligence.&ldquo;Under his tenure, citizens of Nyeri were finally able to conduct business late into the night thanks to his efforts to improve street lighting in trading centres. Governor Gachagua also registered progress in the area of education, initiating a bursary fund that now benefits 10,000 secondary students a year,&rdquo; Uhuru said.Cord leader Raila Odinga said Gachagua was a smart politician with the humility, strength and determination to serve his people. &ldquo;I have very fond memories of the late governor, having worked with him in and out of government in the past,&rdquo; he said.NASA founder Musalia Mudavadi said Gachagua was a diligent and uncompromising person. &ldquo;This quality has manifested itself in his management of Nyeri county as governor and rarely would he fear to stand by his decisions,&rdquo; he said.Gachagua will be remembered for implementing coffee reforms and ensuring better prices for farmers in Nyeri when he was the chairman of the Council of Governors&rsquo; Agricultural Committee.Prior to being elected governor, Gachagua served as Mathira MP from 2002-2007. He was ranked the second-best manager of CDF funds in 2006.